WEBVTT

00:08.520 --> 00:12.520
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:28.140 --> 00:33.420
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:36.000 --> 00:37.720
And here are your hosts.

00:42.120 --> 00:47.200
This is David Carson and Daryl Lane, British-born author James P. Hogan, has gained a reputation

00:47.200 --> 00:50.120
as one of the premier writers of hard science fiction working today.

00:50.560 --> 00:54.980
He's published seven novels so far, including In Here at the Stars, The Gentle Giants of

00:54.980 --> 01:00.020
Gain-A-Meade, Giant Star, Thrice Upon a Time, The Two Faces of Tomorrow, and his latest

01:00.020 --> 01:00.880
Voyage from Yesterday.

01:00.880 --> 01:03.100
Hogan tells us how he became an author.

01:04.200 --> 01:11.580
When I left school when I was sixteen and wanted to be a writer then, I guess it was

01:12.080 --> 01:16.820
something that I always enjoyed doing as a kid at school, you know, the essays and the

01:16.820 --> 01:19.040
story writing exercises you get.

01:21.080 --> 01:24.540
And when I left school I told the world I was going to be a writer.

01:25.600 --> 01:33.000
And you could think of a good idea until somebody said, well, with all the accumulated wisdom

01:33.000 --> 01:36.940
and experience of sixteen years, what are you going to write about that the world is

01:36.940 --> 01:38.260
breathlessly waiting to hear?

01:39.500 --> 01:41.260
And I hadn't thought about that.

01:41.420 --> 01:42.480
The answer was not a lot.

01:43.320 --> 01:48.160
So I went away into engineering and electronics and computers and things like that for something

01:48.160 --> 01:49.040
like twenty years.

01:50.240 --> 01:57.220
And I suppose the interest in writing probably never went away.

01:58.300 --> 02:02.500
For twenty years Hogan worked as a systems designer for computers and sold computers

02:02.500 --> 02:04.340
to scientists for use in their research.

02:04.780 --> 02:08.840
Associating with scientists as he did, Hogan was exposed to all sorts of current scientific

02:08.840 --> 02:13.160
research and he would make use of his scientific contacts when he began to write seriously.

02:13.160 --> 02:20.260
I made use of my customers pretty freely as consultants, which was kind of handy.

02:20.500 --> 02:25.880
I found that I had customers who were brain surgeons and other customers who were studied

02:25.880 --> 02:31.240
pieces of rock brought back from the Apollo missions and other guys who were building

02:31.240 --> 02:34.220
in or investigating machine intelligence.

02:34.480 --> 02:40.200
Just about any of the topics or the favorite themes of science fiction that you could take

02:40.200 --> 02:47.020
out of a hat, the chances were sort of ten to one I had a customer specializing in that

02:47.020 --> 02:51.740
field and I just had to, if I needed some background information on a particular topic

02:51.740 --> 02:56.540
I could almost guarantee I had a phone number in my diary as a guy who could talk all day

02:56.540 --> 02:57.000
about it.

02:58.000 --> 03:02.920
And they loved doing it as well I used to call them and they'd like to come and talk

03:02.920 --> 03:03.440
to you tomorrow.

03:04.440 --> 03:07.100
Well we're a little busy but what's it about?

03:07.100 --> 03:10.120
Oh I need some help with the book I'm working on.

03:10.220 --> 03:11.160
Well why didn't you say so?

03:11.300 --> 03:12.260
What times do you want to show up?

03:12.760 --> 03:13.640
And they talk all day.

03:14.820 --> 03:25.820
I think this is one of the interesting sides of selling computers into this kind of area.

03:26.000 --> 03:32.960
You can imagine some of these specialists they talk to bacteria all day long or whatever

03:32.960 --> 03:38.360
and they end up shutting the back rooms of universities and maybe there are four people

03:38.360 --> 03:43.880
on the planet they can talk to who understand their language and sometimes they find it

03:43.880 --> 03:51.040
hard to believe that somebody from the world outside that has walked in off the street

03:51.040 --> 03:58.160
is sincerely interested to sit down and talk to them and is curious and wants to know

03:58.160 --> 03:59.840
what they're doing, wants to have it explained.

04:00.840 --> 04:05.700
So writing about his experiences with scientists, Hogan found that he was a science fiction writer.

04:07.540 --> 04:12.900
I didn't particularly set out to be a science fiction writer I suppose I became one by accident.

04:13.640 --> 04:18.460
I just always wanted to write and started writing stories about the little bit of life

04:18.460 --> 04:24.240
that I had some personal experience of and was told I was a science fiction writer and

04:24.240 --> 04:24.940
I said how's that?

04:25.220 --> 04:29.480
And they said well the publisher is publishing it under their science fiction influence so

04:29.480 --> 04:33.960
I said okay and it kind of started out like that.

04:35.100 --> 04:37.920
Hogan's books are scientifically accurate and highly realistic.

04:38.320 --> 04:41.080
He's been called the man who put science back into science fiction.

04:41.460 --> 04:44.020
Next time we'll talk to James P. Hogan about some of his novels.

