12:00.020 --> 12:04.760
James P. Hogan's science fiction novel Inherit the Stars was popular enough with readers to justify a sequel.

12:05.080 --> 12:05.840
Two of them, in fact.

12:06.220 --> 12:09.860
The first was entitled A Gentle Giants of Ganymede and it was published in 1978.

12:10.580 --> 12:12.120
Hogan explains why he wrote the book.

12:13.320 --> 12:16.500
When I wrote Inherit the Stars, I had three books in mind.

12:17.040 --> 12:18.500
I had a trilogy in mind.

12:20.200 --> 12:25.380
So I put the hooks in...although Inherit the Stars was a complete story in itself,

12:25.880 --> 12:28.840
it didn't leave the reader hanging.

12:29.100 --> 12:31.860
It started and told and finished a story.

12:32.400 --> 12:35.860
Nevertheless, there were a couple of hooks in there that invited some questions,

12:36.840 --> 12:40.800
which sort of paved the way to a follow-up book.

12:43.420 --> 12:46.820
And my thinking at the time was, I'll go that far,

12:46.940 --> 12:51.880
but I won't write the second book until I have some feedback

12:51.880 --> 12:57.000
as to how the readers liked the first one.

12:57.780 --> 13:00.000
And I got a lot of mail and they all liked it,

13:00.080 --> 13:02.720
and a lot of them said in their letters, will there be a follow-up?

13:02.840 --> 13:03.860
They picked out the hooks.

13:04.420 --> 13:06.180
So I wrote The Gentle Giants.

13:07.060 --> 13:11.600
The Gentle Giants of the title are a race of aliens that first turned up in Inherit the Stars.

13:12.120 --> 13:15.360
In that book, scientists from Earth had discovered a wrecked spaceship on Ganymede,

13:15.980 --> 13:17.420
one of Jupiter's huge moons.

13:17.720 --> 13:21.680
And on it were the remains of prehistoric creatures from Earth, dinosaurs and the like.

13:22.620 --> 13:27.120
In the Gentle Giants of Ganymede, humans meet some live Ganymians who have returned to the solar system

13:27.120 --> 13:31.280
after a mishap in space kept them away for some 25 million years due to time dilation.

13:31.740 --> 13:34.960
It turns out that the Ganymians had been responsible for human evolution.

13:34.960 --> 13:38.580
They'd taken primitive hominids from Earth 25 million years ago

13:38.580 --> 13:40.280
and moved them to a planet called Minerva.

13:41.040 --> 13:43.860
Minerva was then one of the inner planets of our solar system,

13:44.020 --> 13:47.160
but it was destroyed in a tremendous war involving the human stock

13:47.160 --> 13:49.100
that had evolved from the Ganymian experiments.

13:50.220 --> 13:54.060
The second book ends with the Ganymians leaving the solar system in search of their own people,

13:54.420 --> 13:57.920
who migrated from Minerva millions of years before the war that destroyed the planet.

13:58.520 --> 14:00.300
Hogan says readers wanted a third book.

14:01.700 --> 14:07.180
And they wanted another one and I did have a trilogy in mind when I wrote it.

14:07.300 --> 14:09.460
And the third one in that series is now written.

14:09.700 --> 14:13.860
It's called Giant Star and it will be, it's a July title.

14:14.400 --> 14:17.160
So it should start to appear in the bookstores around June.

14:18.440 --> 14:21.500
It's the third and last. There won't be any more in that series.

14:22.600 --> 14:27.420
So it ties up a few of the loose ends, tells another story.

14:30.800 --> 14:36.180
It continues with the characters we met in the previous two books,

14:36.340 --> 14:39.780
both the terrestrial and the alien characters, and introduces some new ones.

14:40.980 --> 14:43.860
And I don't think there can be a fourth one, because it really,

14:44.020 --> 14:45.960
I don't think there's any more to be said. It wraps it all up.

14:51.300 --> 14:53.420
Giant Star was published in 1981.

14:53.420 --> 14:57.720
And as Hogan said, it wraps up all the mysteries and loose ends raised in the first two books.

14:58.240 --> 15:01.360
And it presents an absolutely breathtaking concept of man's origins,

15:02.040 --> 15:05.680
explaining also where man gets his curious nature, his aggressiveness,

15:05.960 --> 15:07.840
and his incredible instinct for survival.

15:08.760 --> 15:11.700
Hogan talks about the underlying purpose of the whole trilogy.

15:12.560 --> 15:18.940
Basically it was an attempt to depict science as it is, or at least as I perceive it.

15:18.940 --> 15:25.020
At the same time, we've added into a story that people who were non-scientists, non-specialists,

15:25.100 --> 15:30.720
would find stimulating and arousing for the curiosity,

15:31.600 --> 15:40.520
even if without trying to turn it into a 250-page lab report or something like that.

15:41.100 --> 15:43.220
And stimulating the books certainly are.

15:43.680 --> 15:46.880
For Shear Granger, the whole Manurvan trilogy, as some have called it,

15:46.880 --> 15:49.640
is matched by a few other works in the field of science fiction.

15:50.080 --> 15:53.240
Isaac Asimov's Foundation trilogy comes to mind as a comparison,

15:53.700 --> 15:55.380
as does Olaf Stapled inside John.

15:56.040 --> 16:00.400
James B. Hogan's Inherit the Stars, the General Giants of Ganymede, and Giant Star.

16:01.180 --> 16:03.780
Contemporary science fiction has little to offer that's any better.

