17:39.620 --> 17:42.300
Time travel is one of the traditional themes of science fiction.

17:42.300 --> 17:45.960
One of the best, certainly one of the most realistic time travel books,

17:46.360 --> 17:49.260
is James Hogan's Thrice Upon a Time, which came out in 1980.

17:50.100 --> 17:53.800
But for some time, for a number of years, in fact, before I wrote Thrice Upon a Time,

17:53.840 --> 17:57.080
I'd been wanting to write a time travel book for a number of reasons.

17:58.160 --> 18:05.420
Firstly, I wanted to attempt to face up to the paradoxes, the logical paradoxes,

18:05.420 --> 18:11.280
once and for all, and answer them without top-outs,

18:11.660 --> 18:14.480
without convenient coincidences,

18:15.520 --> 18:19.700
and without obliging characters who just happen to do the right thing

18:19.700 --> 18:22.440
to make everything come out the way the author said.

18:26.280 --> 18:30.940
And secondly, I wanted to get away from this kind of cliche

18:30.940 --> 18:36.100
of some kind of a conjurer's box, described or described as whatever,

18:36.320 --> 18:39.560
that you jump into and you jump out of and you're in some other time.

18:41.440 --> 18:44.500
We think too many conjurer's boxes, and it seems to me unrealistic.

18:45.720 --> 18:50.300
If I ever build a box like that and I thought it was going to take me to another time,

18:50.840 --> 18:52.960
I certainly wouldn't jump into it and press the button.

18:53.960 --> 18:57.240
I would conduct a long series of tests and experiments first,

18:57.340 --> 18:59.060
and none of that here I was ever thinking to do this.

18:59.680 --> 19:04.560
Hogan wanted to avoid some of the cliches or formulas that characterized most time travel stories.

19:05.640 --> 19:10.180
I think in too many stories, time machines are used like starships.

19:10.320 --> 19:15.680
They're just a device, a vehicle, to get some characters into an unusual environment

19:15.680 --> 19:20.340
and then tell a pretty routine story that would stole them from Greek mythology

19:20.340 --> 19:23.000
or European medieval history.

19:23.560 --> 19:25.860
And the technology doesn't come into the story at all.

19:25.940 --> 19:27.280
They could have gone on a Greyhound bus.

19:27.280 --> 19:29.620
I didn't want to do that.

19:30.100 --> 19:35.280
And so the story was about some physicists who had stumbled upon this phenomenon

19:35.280 --> 19:42.420
and had realized that if what they were seeing meant what they thought it meant,

19:42.640 --> 19:49.540
it meant that they could actually inject information into the past and change the past

19:49.540 --> 19:51.520
with all the questions that implies.

19:53.800 --> 19:59.580
And being proceeded to test this phenomenon

19:59.580 --> 20:02.380
and the pains and very, very strange results.

20:03.380 --> 20:06.720
The strange thing the physicists learn is that they can send messages into the past,

20:06.940 --> 20:08.860
not far into the past, maybe just 10 minutes.

20:09.740 --> 20:12.780
I didn't want it to be a million years or a billion years or

20:14.700 --> 20:19.180
some huge span of time where really nothing that you did could make any difference.

20:19.180 --> 20:21.520
How about a lab bench experiment? 10 minutes.

20:22.360 --> 20:25.960
You can just send a little signal back to yourself 10 minutes ago

20:25.960 --> 20:27.540
and change what you've already done.

20:27.800 --> 20:31.500
This is interesting. You're hard up against the paradoxes now.

20:31.660 --> 20:35.260
You can't find a way around them or duck them.

20:35.380 --> 20:37.200
You've got to answer the question, what happened?

20:38.420 --> 20:42.620
The logic of the whole situation becomes absolutely...

20:43.220 --> 20:46.000
it drives you to the point of insanity trying to figure it out.

20:46.540 --> 20:50.880
It was the logic and the science implied by the time travel theme that fascinated Hogan.

20:51.540 --> 20:53.580
He wanted to approach the concept realistically.

20:54.040 --> 20:56.400
And it's so realistic that you feel after reading the book,

20:56.680 --> 20:59.760
you could go down to Radio Shack and buy the parts to make a time travel machine.

21:00.420 --> 21:03.240
Recently a number of responsible scientists have been speculating

21:03.240 --> 21:05.320
on the actual possibility of time travel.

21:05.900 --> 21:08.340
We asked Hogan if he thought it would ever be a reality

21:08.340 --> 21:10.140
and if his book was meant to be prophetic.

21:11.240 --> 21:13.300
Well, I don't know whether it's prophetic or not.

21:13.640 --> 21:16.580
As it's elaborated in the book itself,

21:17.380 --> 21:20.820
if something like that ever became a fact,

21:21.080 --> 21:24.020
there are some pretty interesting problems that are going to have to be solved.

21:25.020 --> 21:28.600
And our ideas of logic and cause and effect

21:28.600 --> 21:31.980
are going to have to undergo some pretty interesting revisions.

21:32.300 --> 21:36.440
So I'm certainly not setting myself up as a prophet and saying, yes, it'll happen.

21:37.720 --> 21:38.780
Maybe, I don't know.

21:38.860 --> 21:43.220
I think history has shown that impossible or it'll never happen

21:43.220 --> 21:45.920
are very dangerous phrases to use in any context.

