23:27.980 --> 23:31.380
no one surpasses James P. Hogan in scientific accuracy and realism.

23:31.380 --> 23:36.260
Hogan's publisher, Ballantine Books, has advertised him as the man who puts science back in science fiction.

23:36.680 --> 23:40.280
And after reading books like Thrice Upon a Time and The Two Faces of Tomorrow,

23:40.460 --> 23:42.280
you realize how much he deserves that description.

23:42.860 --> 23:44.460
Hogan is also concerned with realism.

23:44.880 --> 23:48.180
With the kind of everyday detail that makes his story, even though it's set in the future,

23:48.340 --> 23:49.420
a totally believable one.

23:49.760 --> 23:52.020
He explains why realistic detail is important.

23:52.580 --> 23:55.560
I think these kinds of details do matter because

23:55.560 --> 24:01.720
if we're putting a story into a futuristic setting,

24:03.480 --> 24:04.280
I think the

24:06.600 --> 24:10.780
little details of background, such as if the guy needs to make a phone tour,

24:10.960 --> 24:13.460
how does he go about it if he needs to render a cab,

24:14.580 --> 24:18.460
these matter because if the story is being told in the future,

24:18.860 --> 24:22.700
the whole of the background has to be consistently futuristic.

24:25.120 --> 24:29.680
I've come across a number of instances, which in my opinion are a little flawed,

24:29.820 --> 24:33.000
because I've dealt with an AW.

24:35.540 --> 24:39.560
A writer may have seized on a particular thought,

24:39.780 --> 24:44.520
maybe a new scientific idea or a machine or whatever,

24:45.160 --> 24:48.240
developed that very well, but kind of gets hung up on it.

24:48.240 --> 24:52.980
In the background, everything else that's going on hasn't changed since 1980.

24:57.120 --> 25:02.060
Trying to stop typing for the five minutes it takes just to think about a situation,

25:02.320 --> 25:05.640
the guy's going to make a phone call, just like stop and think how he might make that,

25:07.540 --> 25:09.640
and think about it for five minutes,

25:09.920 --> 25:16.500
and then maybe show it in a way different to what would have been

25:16.500 --> 25:19.620
the positive thing to do in the first couple of seconds.

25:28.260 --> 25:32.380
Hogan says that his readers appreciate his attention to realistic detail and accuracy.

25:32.720 --> 25:36.780
In fact, he thinks he attracts some readers who don't normally read science fiction because of it.

25:37.940 --> 25:42.000
From the people who write to me and the people that I meet,

25:42.980 --> 25:49.260
one of the gratifying things I observe in the readership that I have is that

25:49.260 --> 25:56.860
it is not confined to what might be termed the hardcore science fiction reader,

25:56.860 --> 26:00.480
who buys anything new that appears on the science fiction section of the bookstore.

26:01.700 --> 26:10.140
But a lot of, I suppose, people who might be termed younger professional people in their late 20s, 30s, 40s,

26:10.140 --> 26:16.680
in all manner of professions, not necessarily to do with the scientists, teachers, lawyers, doctors, so forth,

26:18.060 --> 26:25.240
who typically would say, gee, I used to read science fiction when I was at college or when I was at university,

26:25.240 --> 26:27.180
but I kind of grew out of it.

26:28.300 --> 26:33.800
I can't relate to the way out galaxies like years away anymore or aliens running around with ray guns.

26:34.340 --> 26:39.880
Today I have a family, a career, a mortgage, my feet are solidly on the surface of this planet.

26:40.860 --> 26:46.980
But they seem to like stories that don't kind of try and take them to the other side of the universe

26:46.980 --> 26:50.720
a million years from now, but maybe just stretch the future 20 or 30 years.

26:51.380 --> 26:57.600
And they find names in the book like IBM, Avis, Boeing, familiar places.

26:58.300 --> 27:00.460
And it kind of grabs them.

27:00.460 --> 27:05.860
I say, well, this I can relate to, it's the world that I live in just stretched a little bit.

27:06.060 --> 27:10.900
The connection is not broken, the economics and the politics have evolved from what I read in the papers.

27:11.100 --> 27:12.440
I can still see the connections.

27:13.260 --> 27:16.340
And it could be the world my kids go up in. And I like it.

27:17.360 --> 27:21.540
Hogan's latest novel, Voyage from yesteryear, is further in the future than his other books.

27:21.720 --> 27:25.200
And the field of action is much broader, but it's typically Hogan and his credibility.

27:25.200 --> 27:30.160
If you haven't been exposed to James P. Hogan's brand of science fiction, you're missing something.

